The first virtual operator will arrive in the Czech Republic this year.
Maybe
The mobile market in the Czech Republic is quite advanced and our operators offer almost all services as their partners in Western Europe.
However, we miss something here - a virtual operator that would force the classic to slow down.
It may not be missing for a long time.
About the fact that Czech operators belong to the most expensive in Europe, we have written on Mobil.cz many times.
He also said that the price of SMS is higher than in the rest of the EU.
After the last steps of the European Commission in the field of regulation of roaming fees, there may be a paradox situation - for some customers of Czech mobile operators, SMS from abroad will be cheaper than in the home.
How is it possible that the prices in the Czech Republic remain so high compared to Europe?
The answer is simple, there is a lack of competition that would really want to go into struggle.
It may sound paradoxically, we have three mobile networks and a penetration high over 100%.
Mobile operators, on the other hand, like to rejoice that the Czech market is extremely competitive.
The chairman of the Council of the Czech Telecommunications Office (ČTÚ) Pavel Dvořák often calls for them, who in the past has repeatedly stated that there is no place for another operator in the Czech Republic.
It’s probably true that a classic operator with its own network has no chance (otherwise, it’s probably hard to find frequencies).
But there is another option - a virtual operator.
The entrance of virtual operators to the mobile market has led to a significant price decrease, which the classic operators have also had to respond to.
However, even before the introduction of stick like Tesco Mobile or Virgin Mobile on the market, similar voices sounded in the UK as in us.
But it turned out that the place for such operators is and can be really successful.
There is no need to go too far for examples.
In February of this year, we informed you about the launch of the virtual operator Mobilking in Poland.
In just six months, this operator managed to acquire more than 100,000 customers and become the fifth largest operator there.
At the same time, behind Mobilking stands the financial group Penta, which in the Czech Republic owns among other things U:fona.
The advantage of virtual operators is the ability to focus on a much more specific target group.
In order to operate efficiently, there are fewer customers enough than the traditional operator.
They do not carry relatively high costs for the construction, operation and maintenance of a mobile network.
In the world, virtual operators usually profile as low-cost - they offer cheap calls and SMS, which is often balanced by a narrow offer of services.
For example, Tesco Mobile in the UK offers SMS at least half cheaper than its competitors.
But as the example of Mobilking in Poland shows, it can be a pretty good move and a bet on the untouched target group.
This operator is specifically focused on men.
“Right men choose Mobilking – the operator they like and they can trust,” says David Seibertz, CEO of Mobile Entertainment Company, operating this virtual operator.
It’s hard to say if a similar concept as in Poland could be captured in us.
Vodafone spokesman Miroslav Čepický claims: “The Czech market is relatively small for the segment approach on which most virtual operators are based.
In addition, it is relatively saturated in terms of the offer of services.”
In the Czech Republic no chance, say mobile operators
But it seems almost certain that if there is a virtual mobile operator in the Czech Republic, it will not be Mobilking.
“We are talking about the expansion of this successful project, but in the Czech Republic negotiations don’t look too hopeful.
Instead, the launch of Mobilking will happen in other countries of our region,” said Jana Studničková, a spokesman for the Penta Financial Group, in a telephone interview with Mobil.cz.
She indirectly confirmed that the existing mobile operators in the Czech Republic are definitely not inclined to this idea.
On the contrary, they are trying to do everything in order that no potential competitors arise.
The interest in launching a virtual mobile operator has long been the GTS Novera group, which would like to take a further step towards becoming a real competitor of Telefónica O2 in the field of corporate customers.
“We are very interested in providing not only solid, but also mobile telecommunications services to our customers.
And the sooner, the better.
We have repeatedly discussed this option with all Czech mobile operators.
With some of them we have already managed to progress in negotiations,” said Pavel Kaidl, a spokesman for the group.
Maybe it is going to blink for better times.
According to the report, the first virtual operator is expected to be launched by the end of the year.
For now, however, its creation is accompanied by the untouchable wall of silence.
“At this point, we don’t think that there is a place on the Czech market for the creation of a full-value virtual operator.
The Czech market is very specific compared to other markets.
So far we have not been addressed by any entity with a complex and serious project in this area,” Vlastimil Sršeň from the press department of Telefónica O2 said in a statement to Mobil.cz.
Other operators are also referring to the specificity of the Czech market.
T-Mobile spokeswoman Martina Kemrová adds in rare consensus with the statement of O2: "We have not yet any viable and bilateral profitable business project on which it would be possible to further build."
He added: “In the T-Mobile network, it’s hard to find a virtual operator by the end of the year.
At the moment we should have a concrete agreement on the table so that it is possible to consider in this short-term."
Vodafone rejects its attention rather to meet the requirements of its own 3G license.
Miroslav Čepický says: “Through negotiations with potential virtual operators, we are open, especially in the field of cost sharing and infrastructure.
This is what we think is the most profitable for our customers.
Vodafone’s main strategy in this area is to find a partner to build a shared network for fast mobile internet.”
Responsible authorities - with operators one hand
The procedure of mobile operators can be easily understood, the entry of another operator would mean an increase in competition, leading to a decrease in prices and thus a decrease in their profits.
Why do we make it easier for such competitors?
The fact that when the operators go something, they will be able to pull for one thread, is also witnessed by the tahanice around the formation of the U:fona.
Per the biggest pressure towards CTÚ went at the time of the U:fone from T-Mobile.
This is evidenced by publicly accessible information from the website.
Now, however, just U:fon is suitable as an argument why the virtual operator is not allowed.
Martina Kemrová said: “The competitive environment of the mobile market has recently been further strengthened by the entry of the fourth mobile operator on the market.
Given the character of the mobile market in the Czech Republic, it is clear that the entry of another player would put high demands on him and above all on his services."
Due to this approach of mobile operators, however, the complete disinterest of the Czech regulatory authorities is directly concerned.
It is not just the position of the Czech Republic, which unfortunately in the Czech Republic - unlike the UK and other developed countries - has no authority to interfere with competition.
These are exclusively owned by the Office for Competition Protection (UOHS).
He has a typical attitude to the whole issue.
“Virtual operator’s entry to the mobile market would be possible after a contract between the mobile operator and the virtual operator was concluded for the rental of the necessary infrastructure.
No such agreement has been concluded so far, as the offer of potential stakeholders probably wasn’t interesting enough for the classic operators,” said Kristián Chalupa from the Department of Foreign Relations of the UOHS in response to our question.
The representatives of the operators will probably not be surprised.
From the authority to represent the interests of consumers and, among other things, to ensure that no one abuses its position on the market, it is more than appreciated.
Especially when Kristián Chalupa adds: "In abroad, where virtual operators normally operate, we can observe that their entry into the market contributed to the reduction of prices for mobile telephone services."
Apparently, the pressure on the proper functioning of the market environment and the decrease in prices do not belong to the interests of the UOHS.
In the truth shocking on the whole case is the impressive conspiracy of the three mobile operators, which arises from their reactions.
The question of whether it really is only a coincidence, is proposed by itself.
Just like the exact same price of gasoline at the gas stations is just a part of a coincidence and a hard competitive struggle.
“The Office has not found signs of an anti-competitive action in this case and therefore has no reason to interfere in any way.
None of the operators have a dominant position, therefore they have no appropriate increased responsibility for their actions on the market.
The tools needed to open the mobile market for virtual operators are likely to meet the telecommunications regulator," Chalupa said in a statement.
The interpretation of the dominant position on the market is one of the many controversial points.
There is, of course, an analysis of the relevant markets developed by the CTU, according to which telecommunications are the single market from a competitive point of view.
In such a market, of course, none of the Czech operators have a dominant position.
However, some legal experts offer a different view - the creation of a virtual operator always requires the consent of the network operator.
And the mobile operator - has quite logically - on its network monopoly.
Therefore, in a certain segment it must necessarily be dominant.
Even if we do not admit this argument, it should be at least warning for the UOHS that three mobile operators are doing the same.
At the same time, the complaints of a number of interested parties (including the GTS Novera) show that when negotiating with all operators they face very similar obstacles.
Svaling responsibility on the CTU is a relatively usual trick in telecommunications, which the UOHS gives his hands away from the whole matter.
We have met him in several similar cases.
Unfortunately, until the recent amendment of the telecommunications law, the extension of the powers of the CTU to the field of competition in telecommunications failed to implement, although a number of experts promised to improve the situation.
The representatives of the UOHS must know more than well, but apparently their interests are elsewhere.
It happens when no one looks.
At the same time, the functioning of some pseudo-virtual operators remains unnoticed, which in Czech mobile networks exists just a few.
These are companies issuing their own price lists of mobile telephone services, which are public only partially.
This is usually a multilevel marketing company.
Its own mobile phone services are offered by Amway, Bohemia Telecom, Starlife and many others.
The prices of these companies usually get only to the selected.
The magic lies in the fact that the company faces the operator as a classic corporate customer who orders a large amount of SIM cards.
As a significant customer, he will then receive special price (and other) offers.
The problem is that the business conditions of all Czech mobile operators prohibit similar re-sales.
“If there were cases you’re talking about, it could be a violation of the terms and conditions we’d deal with and it could result in the termination of cooperation with the company,” said Martina Kemrová.
However, it is quite unlikely that such activity would not be carried out to responsible people from mobile operators.
Especially in the case of the three mentioned companies can go for thousands of customers.
None of the operators prevent such a procedure.
These companies have unforgettable profits from their activities and, unlike real virtual operators, do not threaten them with their own official marketing.
Miroslav Čepický warns of possible problems: "The law of similar speculation allows, however, the services of these companies are used by only a small percentage of customers.
In addition, they must accept that the SIM card in their phone is not led to their name, so they cannot have it fully as ordinary customers of mobile operators.”
That should be at least strange.
In addition, another question is opened.
If mobile operators turn their eyes on a similar procedure, why do they block the creation of a virtual operator?
It must be added that the SCO has a relatively strong authority to reveal similar activities, and if it does not wish, it may not be satisfied with the explanation of the operators that they have no idea of anything like this and their business conditions prohibit it.
When is not the most expensive
As it has fallen several times in the text, the entrance of virtual operators to the mobile market has brought a remarkable decline in services prices.
At the same time, practically in all countries where virtual operators were created, classical operators tried to prevent their formation more or less.
The arguments they used were practically identical - too small, possibly too saturated market, problems with the quality of services, etc.
In the developed countries, however, it was just in these moments that regulatory authorities interfered, which defended not the interests of mobile operators, but their customers.
Whether by formal measures or by informal pressure, the first virtual operator was created and the next operator was built.
Unfortunately, the Czech regulatory authorities are throwing the whole case as a hot potato.
From our experience, we cannot get rid of the impression that uncertainty in competencies is more than suitable for them in these cases.
But let’s not throw flint into the grain.
If the background information is correct and the virtual operator will really soon appear, the Czech mobile market may be moving again.
If any of the operators the emergence of some virtual mobile operator has admitted, it will hardly be able to keep the UOHS intact to reject (discrimination) other interested parties.
And we may stop calling drastic than in the rest of Europe.
