Prague MHD on Wednesday for the first time connects to the chip
On Wednesday, October 1, 2008, we will enter the history of the Prague Transport Enterprise as the date when the first passengers to enter the metro, tramways and buses will have an electronic voucher in their pocket instead of a paper ticket.
At the moment, it can buy about a hundred thousand people who own an Opencard chip card.
Passengers can buy a 30-day and 90-day and annual coupon (this will be valid from 1 January 2009) and at the same time let it be uploaded to their chip card in the infocentres and workplaces of the Transport Enterprise at the metro stations Museum, Můstek, Holešovice Station, Angel, Roztyly, Letňany, Kobylisy, Rajská zahrada, Kačerov and Luka.
Coupons can be purchased via the Internet on the website of the Transport Enterprise www.dpp.cz.
More than 400 customers took advantage of the service until the afternoon.
Those who begin to use the internet store can definitely forget the output window in the metro stations, where they have so far had to regularly stand in long fronts on paper tickets.
The coupon is purchased via the internet and on the Opencard card it is recorded in one of the 13 branches of the City Library.
“In these places, passengers are available with a trained service that will help the interested people with online purchases and also upload the purchased coupon to their card,” said project spokesman Martin Opatrný.
In addition to the libraries, it will be possible to upload electronic coupon on Opencard also in self-service machines, which are installed in several vestibules of the metro.
How do these machines look like?
They are red, they remind tickets markers and passengers may have already noticed them at the metro stations Roztyly, Budějovická, I. P. Pavlova, Florenc and Vltavská.
"There are now five in the city, but by the end of the year they should be eighty," he added.
Coupons check the driver's place automatically
The service of the automates that will start working tomorrow is simple.
You just need to insert the Opencard chip card into them and the previously paid coupon will be uploaded on it.
Electronic kupons from tomorrow are valid not only in the capital, but also in its surroundings.
Therefore, in the city trains and bus lines with the numbers 300 to 499, which drive to the capital mainly the inhabitants of the Central Czech municipalities.
"In the trains included in Prague Integrated Transport, the guides are equipped with card readers, using which they determine the timely and band validity of the coupon," explained Filip Drápal from the organization Ropid, which sets the schedules of Prague public transport.
The city buses have card readers built in the driver's box.
Therefore, it is necessary not only to show the chip card to the driver, but also to attach the Opencard to the specified place on the side of the cash.
Thus, the driver will check the validity of the uploaded coupon.
“If the passengers need to verify the validity of the uploaded coupon, there is nothing easier than asking the driver for this information,” Drápal added.
Passengers who do not drive by suburban buses and will not remember when the voucher expires, can go back to the self-service machines where the voucher on the card is recorded.
Here, the information about the validity of their documents will be displayed on the display of the device.
