The rats have feelings.
When a puppy or puppy escapes from a danger, does this mean they also feel fear?
Neurologist Joseph LeDoux is convinced that even many animals have feelings.
But how would it be possible to verify if they feel the same when they behave the same as us?
The internet magazine "Edge" has been publishing contributions of famous scientists for several years.
SPIEGEL ONLINE in its series presents selected answers to the question "What do you think is true without you being able to prove it?"
I believe that animals have feelings and other states of consciousness without me or anyone else to be able to prove it until now, when we can’t even prove that other people have consciousness.
But in this case we can at least hope, because all human brains have the same basic configuration.
However, as soon as we begin to dedicate ourselves to another kind and open questions of perception or general consciousness, we enter the uncomfortable field because the hardware does not match.
When the rats get in danger, they will do the same as many other animals: they will pretend to be dead, escape or attack.
People behave similarly, from which some scientists judge comparable subjective experiences.
However, I do not believe it.
Two aspects of the brain structure make it difficult to transfer our subjective experience to the animal experience.
This is because the circles associated with human consciousness almost always include the lateral prefrontal cortex (for its part in short-term memory and execution or control functions).
This extensive area is significantly more developed in man than in other primates, and it seems that it is completely missing in other creatures.
At least in those aspects of our consciousness that depend on the prefrontal cortex, among them the knowledge of who we are, and the ability to plan and make decisions, there is a reason to assume that a person is different even from other primates.
Another dramatic peculiarity could hide a person’s linguistic essence: because so much of his perception is associated with the language, it is often said that consciousness depends on it.
In this case, animals can be excluded.
But even if the consciousness of the tongue did not matter, the tongue would surely affect it, so the animal consciousness, whatever it is constructed, would probably differ from most states of our consciousness.
Therefore, it is difficult to find out how the consciousness may look at other animals.
When, as something internal and subjective, it cannot be measured or, due to a special hardware, analyzed on the basis of our own experience, its exploration puts us in front of great problems.
Most of my conclusions relate to the content of conscious experience, but besides that there is another aspect of consciousness that should be scientifically easily accessible.
It would be possible to explore the processes in the consciousness of animals regardless of their content, and this is exactly what happens in short-term memory studies in primates, especially on the example of visualization.
But this approach, to which Christof Koch and Francis Crick dedicated themselves, focuses more on the neural corelates of consciousness than on the causal mechanisms: both may be identical, but may also not be.
Interestingly, this approach also emphasizes the importance of the non-frontal cortex for the realization of visualization.
What does that result in the feelings?
I draw them out of the fact that the emotional system, such as the system of fear, is activated in the brain aware of its own activities.
What we call "fear" is, therefore, the mental state in which we are when the activity of the defence system located in the brain (or its consequences, such as physical reactions) takes advantage of the operational memory.
Seeed from this angle, feelings are closely linked to those areas of the cortex that are characterized by the primates, and especially people.
In connection with the linguistic nature, a subtle distribution of perception occurs, because using words and grammatics, we can distinguish and categorize states, to assign them to others alongside ourselves.
On the contrary, for example, Antonio Damasio believes that feelings arise from more primitive activities in the areas of the cortex and brain tribe devoted to physical feelings, similar to Jaak Pankseep, who, however, is more focused on the brain tribe.
Because this network has not changed much during human evolution, it could peacefully participate in the feelings perceived by several animals.
Clearly theoretically, I cannot object to this, but I consider it unproofable.
Pankseep argues that what seems to be fear for rats and humans is likely to feel both organisms the same: but how can it be verified, says Pankseep, whether rats and humans feel the same when they behave the same way?
The sword escapes from the danger - does he also feel fear?
From my point of view, the simplicity of behavior cannot prove the simplicity of experience.
It is true that the neural comparison moves us further: rats and humans have similar brain tribes, on the contrary, the brain does not swab.
But is the brain strain responsible for the feelings?
And even if it was possible to prove it in man: how would we want to prove it in a mouse?
I think rats and other mammals, even swabs (who knows?), have feelings.
I really don’t know how I should prove it.
And because their feelings are probably fundamentally different from those of ours (because human consciousness lies on special circles and on the tongue), I’d rather explore emotional behavior than the emotional perception of rats.
Anyway, in this case, we can wait for progress at the neural level, if we measure the same for rats and humans.
As with rats, I do not explore language and consciousness, I do not explore feelings, for I do not know if they exist.
It can be considered short-looking, but I prefer to move forward rather than repeatedly throw myself against the wall.
I am a practical emotionist.
