Drivers repeatedly caught with alcohol in the blood will have to install "alcolock"
The Ministry of the Interior requires that a driver with three administrative penalties for driving under the influence of alcohol must install a system in his car that will prevent him from starting the car drunk or if he does not breathe.
The proposal came to know in June of this year and is now included in the annual report of the Supreme Prosecutor’s Office, according to which it is a pilot project that will last one year.
Its objective is to return the drivers behind the wheel, so the drivers will also have to pass the course of transport re-training.
In addition to the National Traffic Safety Office, the General Directorate of Transportation (DGT) and the Foundation of the Institute of Technology for Automotive Safety (FITSA) will participate in this experience.
According to statistics, between 30 and 75 percent of drivers accused more than once for driving in drunk again in this state will sit behind the wheel.
Alcolock should prevent this because it is a vehicle-connected system that measures the level of alcohol in the breathed air and prevents the start of the car if the driver fails to breathe before or if the alcohol concentration is higher than the permitted.
The price exceeds €1,000 and the guilty must pay it.
A study conducted in this regard in the U.S. in 2007 showed that in vehicles equipped with this device, the infringements were reduced by 65% during the first year following the introduction.
In Spain, it is estimated that it could save the lives of 115 people every year.
The measures are limited to administrative sanctions for two reasons: to address this behavior before it results in a criminal offence.
And to help its implementation, since the legislation can be carried out in the usual way, the necessary adjustment of the criminal provisions requires a change of the law.
The equipment is not yet available in any sales version on the Spanish market, although it has already been tested in some industrial vehicles and public service vehicles.
It is tomorrow that the Parliamentary Congress will vote on the proposal of the PSOE (Spanish Workers' Socialist Party), in which it is recommended to install this system in school buses, as it is in France.
