The Blood That Is Again Certain
Héma-Québec celebrated its 10th anniversary yesterday, and its president, Dr. Francine Décary, was rightly glad that Héma-Québec became one of the most reliable and most efficient blood suppliers in the world.
First of all, he regained the trust of the public, which was seriously shocked after the polluted blood scandal in the 80s and 90s.
As generally known, the state blood reserve managed by the Canadian Red Cross transfusion committee was contaminated by the immune deficiency virus (HIV) and hepatitis C virus during the 1980s.
Due to this drama and the wave of public misconduct, the Canadian government in February 1994 launched a public investigation, which was chaired by Judge Horace Krever and which was intended to explain the circumstances that led to such a tragedy, and to formulate recommendations that such a disaster should not repeat.
While Judge Krever wiped up with the report, some provinces launched a committee aimed at planning a new system of blood management in Canada.
In Quebec this role was held by the Gélinea Committee.
According to the Gélineau and Krever report, two suppliers were established in Canada: Héma-Québec, which was to be managed by Québec, and the Canadian Blood Company for the supply of all provinces and both territories.
“When Hema-Québec started its activities in 1998, just 38% of people still had confidence in the Québec blood system,” recalls Dr. Décary.
“The situation was disgusting.
With continuous efforts to improve the safety of blood products and continuous work in this area over the coming years, we have regained public confidence,” he says and proudly adds that at the beginning of 2008 Hema-Québec was trusted by almost 94% of the Québec population.
Dr. Decary, however, does not lose the mind that “confidence is something very fragile.”
Since its establishment on 28 September 1998, Héma-Québec has applied the principle of caution.
"Then we were witnessing in Europe the occurrence of many cases of human form of disease of crazy cows, new variants of the disease called Creutzfeldt-Jakob's disease," says a woman who has led the company since its foundation in 1998.
"And we didn't know if this disease could spread through blood.
We therefore rely on one of the basic recommendations of the Krever and Gélineau report, according to which in the case when we don’t know it and when the spread of a serious disease is on the stake, in this case of the Creutzfeldt-Jakob disease, which is characterized by a degeneration of the brain inevitably leading to death, is necessary to take exclusive measures.
In April 1999, therefore, we rejected blood from people who have stayed in the United Kingdom for more than one month since 1980.
A few years ago, it was safe to prove that this disease is transmitted through blood.
This episode, therefore, showed us that keeping the principle of caution was meaningful.”
In 1999, a much more accurate technique for detection of HIV appeared on the market: tests with the use of nucleic acid (NAT), which allow to detect in the donor blood directly the presence of the virus itself, rather than the presence of antibodies on which the tests used before were based.
NAT tests have made it possible to shorten the foolish period between the moment of infection of the patient and the moment when our techniques can detect the first viruses in the blood, the specialist explains.
We could shorten this period to less than a week.
We have significantly reduced the risk that some donors could be infected without knowing it and without getting to know it.
These improvements have made it possible to significantly reduce the risk of getting AIDS through blood transfusion.
The risk of getting HIV-infected blood is now exposed to one in 12 million people.
In other words, this means that before someone is infected with HIV, 12 million blood products will need to be distributed.
Since Hema-Québec distributes 400,000 to 500,000 blood products annually, it will take 24 years before the first case of HIV transmission through a blood product appears.
I think that today we can get or prescribe a blood transfusion necessary to heal,” said Head of Headquarters Hema-Québec.
“The challenge for the next decade is to keep our products safe.
We never know what pathogenic element can appear in the system.
Just last year, the island of Réunion discovered the chikungunya virus, which, like the West Nile virus, is transmitted into the blood by bumping insects.
It is necessary to be constantly cautious," continues Dr. Decary, stressing that in addition to safe supply, Hema-Québec must also count on sufficient supply.
“The needs are growing because the population is aging.
As a result of more aggressive cancer treatment, patients often need a new dose of red blood cells or blood plates.
The ageing population also has consequences for a network of blood donors, which in average consists of only 3 percent of Quebec people who are allowed to donate.”
Every healthy person aged at least 18 years, meeting the criteria of admissibility, but can donate blood only once every 56 days, i.e. six times a year.
On average, 14% of blood donors are unaccepted because they are, for example, AIDS or malaria, and if they have visited the country where they are injured, they are excluded for a year.
With these 3% we can maintain a state that meets the needs of hospitals.
The deficiencies are very rare.
Members of the donor network, however, should be supplemented proportionally to how old they are and can no longer donate blood.
However, convincing people to donate blood is difficult, especially then keeping them and encouraging them to become regular donors.
“Life is so unconnected today that we rarely find an hour to donate blood,” Francine Decary said.
With an annual budget of $297 million, Hema-Québec supplies not only blood products, but also human tissue, such as bone transplants, heart clots, eye bulbs and skin, which is almost exclusively used for large burns.
These tissues are analyzed, processed, and frozen before they are stored at Hema-Québek, which also manages the only public blood bank in Québek.
The pulmonary thread, which was previously considered biomedical waste, flows with blood rich in stem cells that can serve to treat serious diseases, such as leukemia.
“A few weeks ago, we celebrated the deposit of our thousand blood samples in the bank and we expect to take over a thousand each year.
At the beginning of next year, we should start offering them for transplants,” says Dr. Décary, who describes the blood collection program as a very popular one.
"Some mothers are disappointed that they don't have access to it," as Héma-Québec has not enough funds to offer this comprehensive and expensive program to all hospitals in Québec.
