Trumphing Psychology: Why Do We Spend More Money?
At the auctions, customers are willing to spend more money, overestimate the goods.
The neurological and economic foundations of this well-known - and seemingly irrational - behavior have managed to reveal to researchers from the Neurology and Economics Department of the University of New York.
According to their study, published in the journal Science, people don’t want to get behind in an eBay auction type competition, so they prefer to pay too high price.
Research using an experimental auction tried to map the scheme of this "game" in the nervous system.
One group of volunteers waged, the other group participated in a game auction, using the method of functional magnetic resonance (fMRI) to explore the active areas of the brain of the experiments.
In both games, participants could win money, but during the auction game, the important element of which is to break the other side, the whole under the cortex of the brain, called the striatum, began to work intensely when losing.
This brain area, in addition to many other functions, plays a role in the "self-revaluation" mechanism of the nervous system.
The price scrolling is therefore, according to the researchers, possible to explain by an attempt to avoid a sharp striate reaction.
To support their theory, members of the research team of economists conducted a financial cutting-edge investigation.
At the same time, there were three contracts against one partner under different conditions.
The control group was simply informed what the actual value of the product was, and they made the bets.
Additionally, the other group members were promised that if they get out of the game victoriously, they will receive another $15 in reward.
The third group received $15 on the contrary before the auction, but in case of loss, its members also lost the money.
Therefore, the difference between the two groups was all in the fact that one was emphasized in victory and the other in loss.
Members of the group playing "contra loss" were, however, willing to go higher than it was in the control and "winning" group, which confirms the hypothesis of neurologists.
"These findings cannot be derived from any previously existing economic theory.
These have so far explained the phenomena observable in the auctions of joy of victory and avoiding risk.
Only neurological imaging methods have helped us solve the contradiction between these two theories so that we have now reached a third explanation,” said Andrew Schotter, Professor of Economics at the University of New York.
Hepatitis: when to look for a doctor?
Approximately half a billion people worldwide suffer from chronic hepatitis B or C infection, and in Hungary this chronic liver disease is listed among the main causes of death.
The number of home cases of hepatitis infection is estimated at a hundred thousand, but only seven thousand of them are treated.
The name of hepatitis is a summary name of infectious liver damage caused by various viruses.
In their symptoms there are many similarities, characteristic is inflammation of the liver and yellowstone, but the causes of the disease and the disease caused by them differ from each other.
Hepatitis viruses, depending on the causes of the disease, spread in two main ways: type A and type E hepatitis through the digestive system (e.g. infected foods, water), type B, C, D hepatitis and other viruses through blood and body fluids (sperm, vaginal secretion, saliva).
Travellers should in any case be protected by vaccinating against viruses A and B, against viruses type C vaccine does not exist.
Symptoms of hepatitis A appear two to three weeks after eating infected food, usually accompanied by nausea, weakness, abdominal difficulties, desire to vomit.
Then, on the skin and eye whites, a yellowness will be formed, the stools will shine and the urine will be dark.
Every year, a million people worldwide die from a more severe type of disease, hepatic cancer and liver cirrhosis caused by hepatitis B.
The main reason is that, according to estimates, only one in ten infected is medically treated.
Hepatitis C can also have very serious consequences: if not treated, it can lead to liver cirrhosis or liver cancer.
Most infected people don’t even know about their disease, the cause of the disease destroys the liver cells malignantly, so the first symptoms come in many cases until in 20-30 years.
Therefore, timely prevention, regular depistation is very important.
In three groups, this disease occurs much more frequently than the average: among people who suffered blood transfusion before 1991, among drug users and among people with tattoo.
Currently, the estimated global number of individuals infected with the virus of chronic hepatitis C is 200 million.
Since the disease can be demonstrated by a routine laboratory examination, a person should, in case of any symptoms of unknown origin, contact his practical doctor.
With timely detection, the disease is healable, the virus can be removed from the body, thereby preventing infection and preventing the development of cancer.
September 30 is the World Hepatitis Day, which was first organized worldwide by organizations representing the sick in 2004.
It aims to highlight the chronic liver inflammation caused by these viruses, the causes of its formation and the importance of timely diagnosis of the disease.
Who believes in God is not so painful.
According to the results of recent research, faith in God works as a certain analgesic that could facilitate death for already Catholic martyrs.
Scientists from the University of Oxford conducted an interesting experiment, exploring how faith in God affects the perception of pain, the British newspaper Telegraph.
As part of a fairly bizarre survey, 12 Catholic believers and the same number of atheists were subjected to electric shocks, while all observed a painting depicting the Virgin Mary.
According to the results, Catholic believers were able to eliminate a large part of the pain.
Through the technique that thoroughly examined the human brain, it was also shown that Catholics were able to activate that part of their brain that is responsible for regulating pain.
Research is the first of a series of research, which, in addition to academics, participates scientists, philosophers and theologists from different parts of the university.
Exactly the test was conducted by attaching a flashing tool to the left hand of the experimental subject, which issued electrical shocks.
The researchers asked the participants to observe two paintings: Sassoferrat's Virgin Mary from the 17th century and the Lady with Leonard da Vinci's border, painted in the 15th century.
The authors of the research hoped that the sight of the Virgin Mary would trigger a certain state of worship among the believers, while the image of Da Vinci was chosen because it was not too different from the first and they thought it was a calming impression.
The experimental subjects spent half an hour in the MRI scanner and during this time they received 20 electroshocks in four consecutive parts, while separately monitoring the image with a religious or general theme.
The Catholics said they felt “safe” when they looked at the Virgin Mary, as if they were “careful” and “calmed, peace was filled.”
When they watched a religious image, they felt 12 percent less pain than when they had Leonard's work.
Psychologist Miguel Farias, who also participated in the research, believes that a similar effect can be achieved with any strongly impressive image even in the atheists, only it is necessary to find the right photo.
“We should find a picture that they will perceive very positively, from the position of a mother or father,” the psychologist said.
Anglican bishop Tom Wright welcomed the results of the research.
“The practice of faith should change, and in many cases it will also change our personality,” Wright added.
After such great results, it’s just a question what effect it would have on the pain regulation of the believers if they show them some Madonna from Leonard or a painter of a similar calibre.
Would a look at the quality of the Virgin Mary mean achieving even better results?
