Intelligent car imitates flight
What would probably be the best method of developing technologies capable of preventing collisions, unless the imitation of the detectors of obstacles occurring in the world of nature?
For example, in the bees.
The initial strategic idea of the surprising project, presented at the Japanese CEATEC exhibition, was introduced to engineers from the Nissan company. It was about how to build a new generation of collapse preventive systems.
In collaboration with the University of Tokyo, Nissan has built a biomimetic BR23C robotic control system, a robotic mini car equipped with bee properties, with the ultimate goal to help create a system that can eliminate any collapse.
“In the course of the flight, each bee creates its own oval-shaped personal space, which is actually very similar to our safety protective packaging,” said Kazuhiro Doi, the brand’s chief executive for technological PR and research and development.
An important role is played by the complex eyes, which allow birds to see in all directions in a view angle of more than 300 degrees.
To copy the function of the complex eye, the engineers sought the idea of a laser distance meter.
It identifies obstacles at a distance of up to 2 meters before BR23C in the 180-degree vision field, calculates their distance and sends a signal to the board microprocessor that immediately turns into an operation aimed at preventing collision.
The obstacle is captured within a fraction of a second, then the robotic car begins to imitate the movements of the bee and by turning the wheels in the scope necessary to prevent collision immediately changes the direction.
Unlike any existing system, this moving maneuver is conducted in a completely instinctive way.
“If not so, the robotic car would not be able to react quickly enough to avoid obstacles,” explains Tošijuki Ando, head of the Mobility Laboratory and the robotic car project.
It must respond instinctively and immediately, as this technology meets the most vulnerable and inner layer of the safety packaging, within which the collision is currently considered inevitable.
The whole process must reflect what the bee does to avoid other birds.
This process should not take longer than the blindness of the eye.
However, unlike the bees, this movement cannot go up, down or angle, it can only be two-dimensional and only in the direction by which the wheels can be turned.
Instead of the infinite possibilities offered to bees when avoiding, in the case of a robotic car, only the possibility of rotative movement, acceleration and slowing was applied.
BR23C uses lithium-polymer batteries that are lighter and have higher energy density, meaning they have longer life than lithium-ion variants.
According to Andoa, instinctive, intelligent reaction is important, not the ability to process, the less then data storage.
This mechanism must process and respond only to a few input signals per second.
It is not necessary to store and respond using intuitive logic based on data from previous maneuver, therefore it constantly uses only a memory of a few kilobytes size.
It does not need memory with a gigabyte or megabyte capacity.
This is the first step towards the development of a technology for immediate avoidance, which, according to Nissan’s estimates, could get into serial cars within ten years.
Another possibility of application may be the connection of the unit to the GPS satellite navigation system, which, after avoiding obstacles on the road, would lead the driver to the end target.
