The domestic sales prices in the industry increased by 0.1 percent in August 2008 compared to the previous month and 12.9 percent compared to August 2007, the Central Statistical Office.
Export sales prices in the industry were 1.1 percent higher compared to July 2008 and fell 3.9 percent annually.
Production prices in the industry were caused by changes in domestic and export prices by 0.7 per cent higher compared to the previous month, increasing by 3.2 per cent annually.
The domestic sales prices in the industry rose by just a minimum of 0.1 percent compared to the previous month.
Also, domestic sales prices in the processing sectors increased slightly, 0.1 percent, compared to July.
The biggest price increase occurred in August 2008 in the leather and shoe industry (2,8 per cent), mainly due to the monthly price increase in the leather and farm products industry by 4.6 per cent, and the shoe industry by 2.5 per cent.
The higher price levels of plastic and chemical raw materials resulted in a significant monthly price increase in the chemical and product industry (1,6 percent).
The price decrease occurred in the oil processing sector (1,4 percent), the production of electrical machinery and equipment (0,9 percent), as well as - at a minimum - in the woodworking sector (0,1 percent).
The prices in paper production and publishing and printing activities have not changed.
In other industries of the processing industry, we measured a price increase in the range of 0.2 to 0.9 percent.
In the production and distribution sector of electricity, gas and water, which has a large weight in the domestic sales industry, prices increased by 0.3 percent in August, mainly by the continued influence of the officially established increase in the price of gas from 1 July.
In the twelve-month comparison of domestic sales in the different sectors of the processing industry, prices increased most in the professional oil processing sector (32.4 percent).
In the metal-processing industry, a 13.2 percent increase was observed, in the food, beverage and tobacco industry, which has a decisive weight, then a 11 percent increase in prices.
The price decrease occurred in the textile and textile manufacturing sectors (2,5 percent) and in the manufacturing of electrical machinery and equipment (0.3 percent).
In other processing industries, the rate of price growth was between 0.6 and 9.1 percent.
Overall, the price in the processing industry increased by 10.2 percent over the past year.
The prices in the production and distribution sectors of electricity, gas and water exceeded the prices of the previous year by 18.7 percent.
In terms of sector-oriented division, domestic sales showed the highest monthly price increase (0.7 percent) in the sectors involved in the production of material assets in August.
In the consumer goods sectors, prices increased by 0.3 percent, while in the energy processing and further processing sectors, prices did not change compared to the previous month.
The biggest price rise compared to the same month of the previous year was observed in the energy processing and further processing sectors in August 2008 (16.8 percent).
In the consumer goods sectors, we measured a price increase of 6.8 percent, while in the material assets, the price decline of 1.4 percent.
Export sales prices of industrial products measured in forints rose 1.1 percent in August compared to the previous month, down 3.9 percent in the twelve-month comparison.
