Goodbye to the old Paradiso cinema, the city ruins historical halls
The historic cinema halls are closed in favour of the Multiplex.
“A city without cinema is like a blind, it is like a face without eyes.”
The picture offered by Giuseppe Tornator successfully documented what is happening in the big Italian city centers, but also in rural towns.
The process of limiting the cinemas, the birth of large multisals in the suburbs and the subsequent disappearance of monosals in the central zones of cities, is one of the events that seem to be inevitable and irreversible, but also has all the characteristics of a real cultural crime.
“It’s like we’re losing a friend, a friend, with whom we shared a bit of journey and a lot of emotions,” the director of the New Cinema Paradiso, a film that twenty years ago won the Tornator’s Oscar and the Grand Prize of the Jury in Cannes, and that tells the poetry of a village cinema and the sadness for the way of life that the cinema probably lost forever.
The values obtained by Anece, the main association of operators, speak clearly: in the last five years, the door has been closed by 316 cines of the traditional type, and the highest account paid primarily by the halls in the most important cities: 10 less in Florence, 9 less in Milan, Naples, Bologna and Rome, 6 less in Turin, 5 less in Palermo.
Among the regions most affected by closures, Emilia-Romagna is first with the loss of 82 cinemas, followed by Tuscany (44) and Lombardy (41).
And the proof that the first responsible for their disappearance is the emergence of the multiplex, are these three Italian regions that have recorded the highest number of new cinematic multisals: 195 platen more in Lombardy in the last five years, 81 in both Tuscany and Emilia-Romagna.
"The Italian process has evolved irrationally," says Paolo Protti, President of Anecu,"it is useful to create new structures, but it would be necessary to guarantee that the already existing survive, because when one cinema in the city is closed, not all its visitors are willing to move into the multiplex.
Then let’s not even talk about the fund’s insufficient subsidy in favour of operators: the previous state debt is about 10 million euros.
From a moral and ethical point of view, it is a shame that the government does not respect existing laws.
It would require between 16 and 18 million euros per year to support the sector.”
Interesting is the Bologna case, the first Italian city that is concerned with closures and which decided to find a way out by signing a protocol between the municipality and Anec, the first of this type in Italy to protect and promote small cinemas both in historic centers and in the suburbs.
Among the planned standards are tax relief steps in favour of operators and advantages for the audience in terms of mobility: viewers will be able to get into a zone with limited traffic and will have special prices to stop and on some parking spaces.
“I like this initiative,” says Giuseppe Tornatore, “and I hope that other cities will follow the example of Bologna by introducing other measures.”
However, it is certain that in order to stand up against the great power of the multiplex, the traditional halls must improve the quality of sound and image, as today’s audience is more challenging.
The defense of the traditional cinema is a topic that has always been important: the closure of the Super Cinema in Bagheria, instead of my childhood and adolescence, was a brick that convinced me to set up "New Cinema Paradiso", which I have been thinking about for 10 years.
